# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: armour
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:armour/6b47-helmet] The 6B47 was developed by Armokom from 2011 onwards.
[src:armour/6b47-helmet] The company had previously developed and produced the 6B7-1 and 6B7-1M helmets for the Russian army.
[src:armour/6b47-helmet] The helmet provides the ability to use standard communications equipment, and differs from previous helmets in its ability to mount night vision devices and other equipment.
[src:armour/6b47-helmet] It retains its protective properties at temperatures from −50 to +50 °C.
[src:armour/6b47-helmet] Its guaranteed shelf life is at least 8 years, of which the guaranteed service life is at least 5 years.
[src:armour/6b47-helmet] According to Armocom deputy general director Oleg Faustov, the 6B47 is the lightest helmet made by the company.
[src:armour/6b7-helmet] 6B7 helmet was developed as part of Borit-M program in 1990s by NII Stali.
[src:armour/6b7-helmet] Borit program has been started sometime in the second half of 1980s with a task to develop a new composite helmet for the Soviet army as a response to US PASGT helmets.
[src:armour/6b7-helmet] 6B7 is the first generation composite helmet in service with the Russian army, being made out of a composite of aramid fabric and polymer.
[src:armour/6b7-helmet] Discarding steel as a material allowed to make the helmet lighter compared to the previous SSh-68.
[src:armour/6b7-helmet] The helmet provides Br1 protection according to Russian GOST system.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The **7.62×51mm NATO** (official NATO nomenclature 7.62 NATO) is a rimless, bottlenecked, centerfire rifle cartridge.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] It is a standard for small arms among members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO).
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] First developed in the 1940s, the cartridge was introduced in U.S. service in 1954 for the M14 rifle and M60 machine gun.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The later adoption of the 5.56×45mm NATO intermediate cartridge and assault rifles as standard infantry weapon systems by NATO militaries started a trend to phase out the 7.62×51mm NATO in that role.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Many other firearms that use the 7.62×51mm NATO fully powered cartridge remain in service today, especially various designated marksman rifles/sniper rifles and medium machine guns/general-purpose machine guns (e.g.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] M24 Sniper Rifle and M240 Medium Machine Gun).
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The cartridge is also used on mounted and crew-served weapons mounted on vehicles, aircraft, and ships.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Work that would eventually develop the 7.62×51mm NATO started just after World War I when the large, powerful .30-06 Springfield cartridge proved difficult to adapt to semi-automatic rifles.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] A less powerful cartridge would allow a lighter firing mechanism.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] At the time, the most promising design was the .276 Pedersen.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] When it was eventually demonstrated that the .30-06 Springfield was suitable for semi-automatic rifles, the .276 Pedersen was dropped.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Thus, when war appeared to be looming again, only a couple of decades later, the .30-06 Springfield was the only round available, and the M1 Garand provided U.S. troops with greater firepower than their bolt action-armed opponents.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The Garand performed so well that the U.S. saw little need to replace it during World War II, and the .30-06 Springfield served well beyond the Korean War and into the mid-1950s.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The .30-06 Springfield was officially replaced by the 7.62 NATO M14 in 1957.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] During the 1940s and early 1950s, several experiments were carried out to improve the M1 Garand semi-automatic rifle.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] One of the most common complaints was the limited-capacity eight-round en-bloc clip, and many experimental designs modified the weapon to use a detachable box magazine.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Springfield Armory's *T20* rifle was a fully automatic version.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Though not adopted, experience with a fully-automatic Garand laid the groundwork for its replacement.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The test program continued for several years, including both the original .30-06 Springfield round and experimental cartridges.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] During the 1940s, the .300 Savage became the basis for experiments on behalf of the U.S.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Military that resulted in the development of the T65 series of experimental cartridges.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The original experimental case design by the Frankford Arsenal was designated the T65 and was similar to the .300 Savage case, but with less taper.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The experimental cases were made from standard .30-06 Springfield cases, which had slightly less capacity than standard .300 Savage cases because the Frankford Arsenal cases had slightly thicker case walls.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The later T65 iterations were made from shortened .30-06 Springfield cases and were longer compared to the original T65 case, as the .300 Savage has a shorter case length than the resulting 7.62 NATO.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The resulting cartridges provided a ballistic performance roughly equal to the U.S. military .30-06 Springfield 1906 pattern M1906 and 1938 pattern M2 service cartridges.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Over forty years of technical progress in the field of propellants allowed for similar service cartridge performance – firing a 147 grains (9.53 g) bullet at 2,750 ft/s (838 m/s) with 2,468 ft⋅lbf (3,346 J) muzzle energy – from a significantly shorter, smaller case with less case capacity.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The eventual result of this competition was the T44 rifle.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] When the United States developed the T65 cartridge, the British military took a different route.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] They had spent considerable time and effort developing the intermediate-power .280 British (7 mm) cartridge with an eye towards controllable fully automatic fire.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The U.S. held to its desire not to reduce the effectiveness of individual aimed shots.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The American philosophy was to use automatic fire only in emergencies and continue to use semi-automatic fire for the majority of the time.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] After considerable debate, the Canadian Army announced they would be happy to use the .280 but only if the U.S. did as well.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] It was clear the U.S. was not going to use the .280 British.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The British did start introducing the .280 British along with the bull-pup Rifle No.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] 9, but the process was stopped in the interests of harmonization across NATO.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The T65E5 (7.62×51mm) was chosen as NATO's standard cartridge in 1954.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Winchester saw a market for a civilian model of the late T65 series designs and introduced it in 1952, two years before NATO adopted the T65E5 experimental cartridge iteration as 7.62×51mm NATO in 1954.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Winchester branded the cartridge and introduced it to the commercial hunting market as the .308 Winchester.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The dimensions of .308 Winchester are almost the same as those of 7.62×51mm NATO.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The chamber of the former has a marginally shorter headspace and thinner case walls than the latter, due to changes in specifications between 1952 and 1954.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] This allows 7.62×51mm NATO ammunition to feed reliably in rifles chambered for .308 Winchester, but can cause .308 Winchester ammunition cases to rupture when fired in rifles chambered for 7.62×51mm NATO.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The T44 rifle was adopted as the M14 rifle in 1957.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Around the same time, Britain and Canada adopted the Belgian FN FAL (L1A1 SLR British) as the L1, followed by the West German army designated as the G1.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The Germans soon transitioned to a modified version of the Spanish CETME rifle by Heckler & Koch that was adopted as the G3.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] With all of these firearms, it was clear that the 7.62×51mm NATO could not be fired controllably in fully automatic because of recoil.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Both the M14 and FAL were later modified to limit fully automatic fire by introducing semi-automatic versions or selector locks.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Efforts were also made to improve control with bipods or heavier barrels.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] *Project SALVO* concluded that a burst of four rounds into a 20-inch (51 cm) circle would cause twice the number of casualties as a fully automatic burst by one of these rifles, regardless of the size of the round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] They suggested using a much smaller, .22 caliber, cartridge with two bullets per cartridge (a *duplex load*).
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] At the same time, other researchers investigated the promising flechette rounds that were lighter but offered better penetration than even the .30-06.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] When the M14 arrived in Vietnam, it was found to have a few disadvantages.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The rifle's overall length was not well-suited for jungle warfare.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Also, the weight of 7.62×51mm NATO cartridges limited the total amount of ammunition that could be carried in comparison with the 7.62×39mm cartridge of the Type 56 and AK-47 rifles, with which the Vietcong and North Vietnamese Army soldiers were equipped.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Fighting between the big-round and small-round groups reached a peak in the early 1960s, when test after test showed the .223 Remington (M193 5.56×45mm) cartridge fired from the AR-15 allowed an eight-soldier unit to outgun an 11-soldier unit armed with M14s at ranges closer than 300 m (328 yd).
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] U.S. troops were able to carry more than twice as much 5.56×45mm ammunition as 7.62×51mm NATO for the same weight, which allowed them an advantage against a typical NVA unit armed with Type 56-1s.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Army began replacing its M14s with M16s, causing further compatibility issues.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Regardless of the M14 having disadvantages in jungle warfare, 7.62×51mm NATO rifles stayed in military service around the world due to several factors.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The 7.62×51mm NATO has proved much more effective than 5.56×45mm NATO at long ranges, and has since found popularity as a sniping round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] For instance, the Mk 14 Enhanced Battle Rifle, an M14 variant, and the M25 sniper rifle were utilized in the United States military as designated marksman and sniper rifles, respectively.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Shorter, easier-to-handle 7.62mm rifles like the G3 stayed in service due to their accuracy, range, cartridge effectiveness, and reliability.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] In addition, continued if limited use in infantry rifles is a logistical convenience, given the preference for 7.62×51mm NATO across NATO for general-purpose machine guns.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Specialized loadings were created for 7.62×51mm NATO-chambered sniper rifles.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] They used heavier and more aerodynamic bullets that had a higher ballistic coefficient than standard ball rounds, meaning they shed velocity at longer ranges more gradually.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Maintaining velocity is important for accurate long-range shots because dropping from supersonic to transonic speeds disturbs the flight of the bullet and adversely affects accuracy.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The standard M80 ball round weighs 147 gr and, from an M14 rifle and M60 machine gun, has a muzzle velocity 200 ft/s (61 m/s) faster than the M118LR 175 gr sniping round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] However, the M80 drops to subsonic velocity around 900 m (984 yd), while the initially slower M118LR is supersonic out to 1,000 m (1,094 yd) due to its low-drag bullet.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The 7.62×51mm NATO round remains in use in designated marksman rifles such as the Heckler & Koch HK417, SIG 716, FN SCAR, L129A1, Colt Canada C20 DMR and LMT MARS-H based riles to take advantage of the effective range and accuracy potential compared with intermediate rifle rounds.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Designated marksman rifles have to be effective, in terms of hit rates and terminal ballistics, at application ranges exceeding those of ordinary assault rifles and battle rifles, but do not require the extended-range performance of a dedicated sniper rifle.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Depending on the military, specialized 7.62×51mm NATO ammunition is sometimes issued to the designated marksman.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The 7.62×51mm NATO round nevertheless met the designers' demands for fully automatic reliability with a full-power round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] It remains the main medium machine gun and general-purpose machine gun round for almost all NATO forces, even being used in adapted versions of older .30-06 Springfield machine guns, such as the WWII-era Browning M1919A4.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The .303 British Bren gun was also converted to fire the 7.62×51mm NATO round, and the converted weapon was reclassified as the L4 Light machine gun.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] West Germany rechambered many of its WW2-era MG42s to create the MG2, and the succeeding MG3 is essentially a slightly modified version of the same weapon.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] These have been largely replaced in the light machine gun role by 5.56×45mm NATO weapons, such as the widespread use of the M249 SAW.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] However, the 7.62×51mm NATO fully powered cartridge is still the standard chambering for the M134 Minigun and GPMGs such as the M60E4, FN MAG/M240, HK21, MG3, AA-52, Vektor SS-77, UKM-2000 and MG5 and flexible mountings such as helicopters, jeeps, and tanks.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] It is also commonly found in coaxial mount applications, such as parallel to the main gun on tanks.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The characteristics of 7.62 mm bullet types were not only researched in the 20th century but were also studied in the 21st century.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Army developed an improved version of the M80 7.62mm ball round, designated the *M80A1*.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The M80A1 incorporates changes found in the M855A1 5.56 mm round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Like the M855A1, the M80A1 has better hard-target penetration, more consistent performance against soft targets, and significantly greater ranges of these effects than the M80.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The bullet is redesigned with a copper jacket and exposed hardened steel penetrator, eliminating 114.5 grains (7.4 g) of lead with production of each M80A1 projectile.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The M80A1 began fielding in September 2014.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The Army plans to replace both the M80A1 Enhanced Performance Round and M993 Armor Piercing round with the *XM1158 Advanced Armor Piercing Round* (ADVAP) beginning in 2020.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Its type designation progressed to M1158 and it has been in low-rate initial production since May 2019.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Special Operations Command plans to begin fielding of the 6.5mm Creedmoor cartridge in early 2019 to replace the 7.62×51mm NATO round in semi-automatic sniper rifles.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Tests determined that compared to the 7.62×51mm NATO (M118LR long-range 7.62×51mm NATO load), the 6.5mm Creedmoor doubles hit probability at 1,000 m (1,094 yd), increases effective range by nearly half, reduces wind drift by a third, and has less recoil.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The same rifles can use the new cartridge, as their similar dimensions allow the same magazines to be used and the weapon only requires a barrel change.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The 7.62×51mm NATO has a 3.38 mL (52.0 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The exterior shape of the case was designed to promote reliable case feeding and extraction in bolt-action rifles and machine guns alike, under extreme conditions.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Americans would define the shoulder angle at alpha/2 = 20 degrees.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 305 mm (1 in 12 in), 4 grooves, Ø lands = 7.62 mm, Ø grooves = 7.82 mm, land width = 4.47 mm.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The primer type can be Berdan or Boxer Large Rifle.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) research papers on the influence of Berdan and Boxer primer spit-hole diameter on 7.62-mm cartridge performance concluded the primary advantage of a Berdan primer is that they are less expensive than a Boxer primer due to their reduced complexity.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The ARL found little variation in the pressure-time curves across the different spit-hole configurations.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Doubling the area of the spit-hole or incorporating a Berdan-style spit-hole with the same total area as a standard M80 round showed minimal effects on the overall performance.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The standard Boxer primed M80 showed the best results.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] All measured differences are within one standard deviation and are not significant.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] According to the official NATO EPVAT NAAG-LG/3-SG/1 rulings, the 7.62×51mm NATO can handle up to 415.00 MPa (60,191 psi) Pmax piezo pressure.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The proof round pressure requirement is 521.30 MPa (75,608 psi) piezo pressure recorded in a NATO design EPVAT barrel with a Kistler 6215 transducer, HPI GP6 transducer, or by equipment to C.I.P. requirements.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The 7.62×51mm NATO cartridge approaches the ballistic performance of the original U.S. military .30-06 Springfield M1906 service cartridge.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Modern propellants enabled similar performance in a smaller case with less case capacity, one that requires less brass and yields a shorter cartridge.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] This shorter cartridge allows a slight reduction in the size and weight of firearms that chamber it, and better cycling in automatic and semi-automatic rifles.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Although originating from an identical preceding series of experimental cartridges, the commercial 1952 .308 Winchester and the military 1954 7.62×51mm NATO chamberings have evolved separately but remain similar enough that they can be loaded into rifles chambered for the other round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Still, the .308 Winchester cartridges are typically loaded to higher pressures than 7.62×51mm NATO service cartridges.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Current unlinked ammunition is supplied in M19A1 boxes containing 200 rounds divided across four bandoliers containing five-round charger clips or 300 rounds divided across eight cartons.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Linked ammunition has been primarily supplied in M19A1 boxes containing one 200-round belt each; the belt can consist either of ball rounds only or of a sequence of four ball rounds followed by one tracer.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Historically, both linked and unlinked rounds have also been supplied in wooden boxes containing 500 rounds in bandoliers.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Packaging configurations for all ammunition natures c.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] 2010 consisted of a plastic 8217 box containing 1,260 rounds, divided across nine PVC bags of seven twenty-round cartons each, and a conventional M2A1 box containing 400 rounds, divided across twenty cartons of twenty rounds each.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Link types used included M13, M2A2 Browning, and Vickers.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Much like the .303 ammunition it succeeded, initial batches of British 7.62mm unlinked ammunition were packed in steel H50 boxes, each containing two wooden H51 boxes; each H51 box stored the ammunition in a further H52 metal lining.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Packaging quantities included 700 rounds in bandoliers containing five-round charger clips (350 rounds per H51), 600 rounds in thirty-round cartons (300 rounds per H51), and 576 rounds in cartons containing thirty-two rounds (288 rounds per H51).
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Alternatively, ammunition could be provided in a wooden box containing two metal boxes that were similar but not identical to the H52; these wooden boxes used the same packaging quantities as their H50 counterparts.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Linked ammunition has been consistently packed in H82 boxes containing one 200-round belt each, with such boxes appearing as early as c.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] 1964; this belt can consist purely of one ammunition nature, but more commonly it consists of a sequence of four ball rounds followed by one tracer round or, more rarely, one ball round followed by one tracer round.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Unless stated otherwise, all ammunition listed below is or was manufactured by Radway Green and by Kynoch.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] Radway Green, which is currently owned by BAE Systems, continues to produce ammunition for the Ministry of Defence and export customers.
[src:armour/7-62-51-nato] The US Armed Forces and NATO use this four-character alphanumeric code to identify the cartridge, the cartridge type, and the packing method (cartons, clips, link belt, or bulk) used.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The **Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II**, also widely known by the nickname **Warthog**, is a single-seat, twin-turbofan, straight-wing, subsonic attack aircraft developed by Fairchild Republic for the United States Air Force (USAF).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In service since 1977, it is named after the Republic P-47 Thunderbolt strike-fighter of World War II, but is commonly referred to as the "Warthog".
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 was designed to provide close air support (CAS) to ground troops by attacking enemy armored vehicles, tanks, and other ground forces; it is the only production-built aircraft designed solely for CAS to have served with the U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Its secondary missions include combat search and rescue, and to direct other aircraft in attacks on ground targets, a role called forward air controller (FAC)-airborne; aircraft used primarily in this role are designated OA-10.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It also performs reconnaissance, air interdiction, and maritime surface warfare missions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 was intended to improve on the performance and firepower of the Douglas A-1 Skyraider.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The Thunderbolt II's airframe was designed around the high-power 30 mm GAU-8 Avenger rotary autocannon.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The airframe was designed for durability, with measures such as 1,200 pounds (540 kg) of titanium armor to protect the cockpit and aircraft systems, enabling it to absorb damage and continue flying.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Its ability to take off and land from relatively short and unpaved runways permits operation from airstrips close to the front lines, and its simple design enables maintenance with minimal facilities.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It served in Operation Urgent Fury in Grenada, the Gulf War (Operation Desert Storm), the Yugoslav Wars, war in Afghanistan, the Iraq War, in the conflict against the Islamic State in the Middle East, Operation Odyssey Dawn in Libya, and the 2026 Iran war.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10A single-seat variant was the only version produced, though one pre-production airframe was modified into the YA-10B twin-seat prototype to test an all-weather night-capable version.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2005, a program was started to upgrade the remaining A-10A aircraft to the A-10C configuration, with modern avionics for use with precision weaponry.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Air Force had stated the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II would replace the A-10 as it entered service, but this remains highly contentious within the USAF and in political circles.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF gained congressional permission to start retiring A-10s in 2023, but further retirements were paused until the USAF can demonstrate that the A-10's close-air-support capabilities can be replaced.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The development of conventionally armed attack aircraft in the United States stagnated after World War II, as design efforts for tactical aircraft focused on the delivery of nuclear weapons using high-speed designs such as the McDonnell F-101 Voodoo and Republic F-105 Thunderchief.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] As the U.S. military entered the Vietnam War, its main ground-attack aircraft was the Korean War-era Douglas A-1 Skyraider.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A capable aircraft for its era, with a relatively large payload and long loiter time, the propeller-driven design had become relatively slow, vulnerable, particularly to ground fire, and incapable of providing adequate firepower.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Air Force and Navy lost some 266 A-1s in action in Vietnam, largely from small-arms fire.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The lack of modern conventional attack capability prompted calls for a specialized attack aircraft.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 7 June 1961, the Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara ordered the USAF to develop two tactical aircraft, one for the long-range strike and interdictor role, and the other focusing on the fighter-bomber mission.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The former was the Tactical Fighter Experimental (TFX) intended to be a common design for the USAF and the US Navy, which emerged as the General Dynamics F-111 Aardvark, while the second was filled by a version of the U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Navy's McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] While the Phantom went on to be one of the most successful fighter designs of the 1960s and proved to be a capable fighter-bomber, its short loiter time was a major problem, as was its poor low-speed performance, albeit to a lesser extent.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It was also expensive to buy and operate, with a flyaway cost of $2 million in FY1965 ($20.4 million today), and operational costs over $900 per hour ($9,000 per hour today).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] After a broad review of its tactical force structure, the USAF decided to adopt a low-cost aircraft to supplement the F-4 and F-111.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It first focused on the Northrop F-5, which had air-to-air capability.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A 1965 cost-effectiveness study shifted the focus from the F-5 to the less expensive A-7D variant of the LTV A-7 Corsair II, and a contract was awarded.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] However, this aircraft doubled in cost with demands for an upgraded engine and new avionics.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During this period, the United States Army had been introducing the Bell UH-1 Iroquois into service.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] First used in its intended role as a transport, it was soon modified in the field to carry more machine guns in what became known as the helicopter gunship role.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] This proved effective against the lightly armed enemy, and new gun and rocket pods were added.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Soon the Bell AH-1 Cobra was introduced.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] This was an attack helicopter armed with long-range BGM-71 TOW missiles able to destroy tanks from outside the range of defensive fire.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The helicopter was effective and prompted the U.S. military to change its defensive strategy in Europe into blunting any Warsaw Pact advance with anti-tank helicopters instead of the tactical nuclear weapons that had been the basis for NATO's battle plans since the 1950s.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The Cobra was a quickly-made helicopter based on the UH-1 Iroquois and was introduced in the mid-1960s as an interim design until the U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Army's "Advanced Aerial Fire Support System" helicopter could be delivered.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The Army selected the Lockheed AH-56 Cheyenne, a more capable attack aircraft with greater speed for initial production.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The development of the anti-tank helicopter concerned the USAF; a 1966 USAF study of existing close air support (CAS) capabilities revealed gaps in the escort and fire suppression roles that the Cheyenne could fill.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The study concluded that the service should acquire a simple, inexpensive, dedicated CAS aircraft at least as capable as the A-1, and that it should develop doctrine, tactics, and procedures for such aircraft to accomplish the missions for which the attack helicopters were provided.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] McConnell, Chief of Staff of the USAF, ordered that a specialized CAS aircraft be designed, developed, and obtained.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 22 December, a Requirements Action Directive was issued for the A-X CAS airplane, and the Attack Experimental (A-X) program office was formed.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 6 March 1967, the USAF released a request for information to 21 defense contractors for the A-X.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In May 1970, the USAF issued a modified, more detailed request for proposals for the aircraft.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The threat of Soviet armored forces and all-weather attack operations had become more serious.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The requirements now included that the aircraft would be designed specifically for the 30 mm rotary cannon.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The RFP also specified a maximum speed of 460 mph (400 kn; 740 km/h), takeoff distance of 4,000 feet (1,200 m), external load of 16,000 pounds (7,300 kg), 285-mile (460 km) mission radius, and a unit cost of US$1.4 million ($11.6 million today).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-X would be the first USAF aircraft designed exclusively for CAS.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During this time, a separate RFP was released for A-X's 30 mm cannon with requirements for a high rate of fire (4,000 rounds per minute) and a high muzzle velocity.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Six companies submitted aircraft proposals, with Northrop and Fairchild Republic in Germantown, Maryland, selected to build prototypes: the YA-9A and YA-10A, respectively.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] General Electric and Philco-Ford were selected to build and test GAU-8 cannon prototypes.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Two YA-10 prototypes were built in the Republic factory in Farmingdale, New York, and first flown on 10 May 1972 by pilot Howard "Sam" Nelson.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Production A-10s were built by Fairchild in Hagerstown, Maryland.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] After trials and a fly-off against the YA-9, on 18 January 1973, the USAF announced the YA-10's selection for production.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] General Electric was selected to build the GAU-8 cannon in June 1973.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The YA-10 had an additional fly-off in 1974 against the Ling-Temco-Vought A-7D Corsair II, the principal USAF attack aircraft at the time, to prove the need for a new attack aircraft.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The first production A-10 flew in October 1975, and deliveries commenced in March 1976.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] One experimental two-seat A-10 Night Adverse Weather (N/AW) version was built by Fairchild by converting the first Demonstration Testing and Evaluation (DT&E) A-10A for consideration by the USAF.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It included a second seat for a weapon systems officer responsible for electronic countermeasures (ECM), navigation and target acquisition.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The N/AW version did not interest the USAF or export customers.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The two-seat trainer version was ordered by the USAF in 1981, but funding was canceled by U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The only two-seat A-10 resides at Edwards Air Force Base's Flight Test Center Museum.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 10 February 1976, Deputy Secretary of Defense Bill Clements authorized full-rate production while the first A-10 was accepted by the USAF Tactical Air Command on 30 March 1976.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Production continued and reached a peak rate of 13 aircraft per month.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] By 1984, 715 airplanes, including 2 prototypes and 6 development aircraft, had been delivered.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] When full-rate production was first authorized, the A-10's planned service life was 6,000 hours.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A small design reinforcement was quickly adopted when initial fatigue testing failed at 80% of testing; the A-10 passed fatigue tests with the fix.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] 8,000-flight-hour service lives were becoming common at the time, so fatigue testing of the A-10 continued with a new 8,000-hour target.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Testing to this new level quickly discovered serious cracks at Wing Station 23 (WS23) where the outboard portions of the wings are joined to the fuselage.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The first production change was to address this problem by adding cold working at WS23.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Soon after, the USAF found that the real-world A-10 fleet fatigue was harsher than estimated, forcing a change to fatigue testing and introduced "spectrum 3" equivalent flight-hour testing.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Spectrum 3 fatigue testing started in 1979.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] This round of testing quickly determined that more drastic reinforcement would be needed.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The second change in production, starting with aircraft No.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] 442, was to increase the thickness of the lower skin on the outer wing panels.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A tech order was issued to retrofit the "thick skin" to the whole fleet, but the tech order was rescinded after roughly 242 planes, leaving about 200 planes with the original "thin skin".
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] 530, cold working at WS0 was performed, and this retrofit was performed on earlier aircraft.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A fourth, even more drastic change was initiated with aircraft No.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] 582, again to address the problems discovered with spectrum 3 testing.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] This change increased the thickness of the lower skin on the center wing panel, but it required modifications to the lower spar caps to accommodate the thicker skin.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF found it economically unfeasible to retrofit earlier planes with this modification.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 has received many upgrades since entering service.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 1978, it received the Pave Penny laser receiver pod, mounted on a pylon attached below the right side of the cockpit, which receives reflected laser radiation from laser designators to allow the aircraft to deliver laser-guided munitions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 1980, the A-10 began receiving an inertial navigation system.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In the early 1990s, the A-10 began to receive the Low-Altitude Safety and Targeting Enhancement (LASTE) upgrade, which provided computerized weapon-aiming equipment, an autopilot, and a ground-collision warning system.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 1999, aircraft began receiving Global Positioning System navigation systems and a multi-function display.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The LASTE system was upgraded with an Integrated Flight & Fire Control Computer (IFFCC).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 1987, Grumman Aerospace took over support for the A-10 program.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 1993, Grumman updated the damage tolerance assessment and Force Structural Maintenance Plan and Damage Threat Assessment.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Over the next few years, problems with wing structure fatigue, first noticed in production years earlier, began to come to the fore.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Implementation of the maintenance plan was greatly delayed by the base realignment and closure commission (BRAC), which led to 80% of the original workforce being let go.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During inspections in 1995 and 1996, cracks at the WS23 location were found on many A-10s; while many were in line with updated predictions from 1993, two of these were classified as "near-critical" size, well beyond predictions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In August 1998, Grumman produced a new plan to address these issues and increase life span to 16,000 hours.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] This led to the "HOG UP" program, which commenced in 1999.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Additional aspects were added to HOG UP over time, including new fuel bladders, flight control system changes, and engine nacelle inspections.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2001, the cracks were reclassified as "critical", which meant they were considered repairs and not upgrades, which allowed bypassing normal acquisition channels for more rapid implementation.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] An independent review of the HOG UP program, presented in September 2003, concluded that the data on which the wing upgrade relied could no longer be trusted.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Shortly thereafter, fatigue testing on a test wing failed prematurely and also mounting problems with wings failing in-service inspections at an increasing rate became apparent.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF estimated that they would run out of wings by 2011.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Of the plans explored, replacing the wings with new ones was the least expensive, at an initial cost of $741 million and a total cost of $1.72 billion over the program's life.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2005, a business case was produced with three options to extend the fleet's life.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The first two options involved expanding the service life extension program (SLEP) at a cost of $4.6 billion and $3.16 billion, respectively.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The third option, worth $1.72 billion, was to build 242 new wings and avoid the need to expand the SLEP.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2006, option 3 was chosen and Boeing won the contract.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The base contract is for 117 wings with options for 125 additional wings.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2013, the USAF exercised a portion of the option to add 56 wings, putting 173 wings on order with options remaining for 69 additional wings.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In November 2011, two A-10s flew with the new wings fitted.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The new wings improved mission readiness, decreased maintenance costs, and allowed the A-10 to be operated up to 2035 if necessary.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Re-winging work was organized under the Thick-skin Urgent Spares Kitting (TUSK) Program.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2014, as part of plans to retire the A-10, the USAF considered halting the wing replacement program to save an additional $500 million; however, by May 2015 the re-winging program was too advanced to be financially efficient to cancel.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Boeing stated in February 2016 that the A-10 could operate to 2040 with the new TUSK wings.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] From 2005 to June 2011, the entire fleet of 356 A-10s and OA-10s were modernized in the Precision Engagement program and redesignated A-10C.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The Government Accountability Office in 2007 estimated the cost of upgrading, refurbishing, and service life extension plans to total $2.25 billion through 2013.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In July 2010, the USAF issued Raytheon a contract to integrate a Helmet Mounted Integrated Targeting (HMIT) system into the A-10C.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The LASTE system was replaced with the integrated flight and fire control computer (IFFCC) included in the PE upgrade.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Throughout its life, multiple software upgrades have been made.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] While this work was to be stopped under plans to retire the A-10 in February 2014, Secretary of the Air Force Deborah Lee James ordered that the latest upgrade, designated Suite 8, continue in response to congressional pressure.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Suite 8 software includes IFF Mode 5, which modernizes the ability to identify the A-10 to friendly units.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Additionally, the Pave Penny pods and pylons were removed as their receive-only capability has been replaced by the AN/AAQ-28(V)4 LITENING AT targeting pods or Sniper XR targeting pod, which both have laser designators and laser rangefinders.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2012, Air Combat Command requested the testing of a 600-US-gallon (2,300 L; 500 imp gal) external fuel tank which would extend the A-10's loitering time by 45–60 minutes; flight testing of such a tank had been conducted in 1997 but did not involve combat evaluation.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Over 30 flight tests were conducted by the 40th Flight Test Squadron to gather data on the aircraft's handling characteristics and performance across different load configurations.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It was reported that the tank slightly reduced stability in the yaw axis, but there was no decrease in aircraft tracking performance.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 has a cantilever low-wing monoplane wing with a wide chord.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It has superior maneuverability at low speeds and altitude due to its large wing area, high wing aspect ratio, and large ailerons.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The wing also allows short takeoffs and landings, permitting operations from austere forward airfields near front lines.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 can loiter for extended periods and operate under 1,000-foot (300 m) ceilings with 1.5-mile (2.4 km) visibility.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It typically flies at a relatively low speed of 300 knots (350 mph; 560 km/h), which makes it a better platform for the ground-attack role than fast fighter-bombers, which often have difficulty targeting small, slow-moving targets.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The leading edge of the wing has a honeycomb structure panel construction, providing strength with minimal weight; similar panels cover the flap shrouds, elevators, rudders and sections of the fins.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The skin panels are integral with the stringers and are fabricated using computer-controlled machining, reducing production time and cost.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Combat experience has shown that this type of panel is more resistant to damage.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The skin is not load-bearing, so damaged skin sections can be easily replaced in the field, with makeshift materials if necessary.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The ailerons are at the far ends of the wings for greater rolling moment and have two distinguishing features: The ailerons are larger than is typical, almost 50 percent of the wingspan, providing improved control even at slow speeds; the aileron is also split, making it a deceleron.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 is designed to be refueled, rearmed, and serviced with minimal equipment.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Its simple design enables maintenance at forward bases with limited facilities.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] An unusual feature is that many of the aircraft's parts are interchangeable between the left and right sides, including the engines, main landing gear, and vertical stabilizers.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The sturdy landing gear, low-pressure tires and large, straight wings allow operation from short rough strips even with a heavy aircraft ordnance load, allowing the aircraft to operate from damaged airbases, flying from taxiways, or even straight roadway sections.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The front landing gear is offset to the aircraft's right to allow placement of the 30 mm cannon with its firing barrel along the centerline of the aircraft.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During ground taxi, the offset front landing gear causes the A-10 to have dissimilar turning radii; turning to the right on the ground takes less distance than turning left.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The wheels of the main landing gear partially protrude from their nacelles when retracted, making gear-up belly landings easier to control and less damaging.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] All landing gears retract forward; if hydraulic power is lost, a combination of gravity and aerodynamic drag can lower and lock the gear in place.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 is able to survive direct hits from armor-piercing and high-explosive projectiles up to 23 mm.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It has double-redundant hydraulic flight systems, and a mechanical system as a backup if hydraulics are lost.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Flight without hydraulic power uses the manual reversion control system; pitch and yaw control engages automatically, and roll control is pilot-selected.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In manual reversion mode, the A-10 is sufficiently controllable under favorable conditions to return to base, though control forces are greater than normal.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It is designed to be able to fly with one engine, half of the tail, one elevator, and half of a wing missing.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] As the A-10 operates close to enemy positions, making it an easy target for man-portable air-defense system (MANPADS), surface-to-air missiles (SAMs), and enemy aircraft, it carries both flares and chaff cartridges.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The cockpit and parts of the flight-control systems are protected by 1,200 lb (540 kg) of titanium aircraft armor, referred to as a "bathtub".
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The armor has been tested to withstand strikes from 23 mm (0.91 in) cannon fire and some indirect hits from 57 mm (2.2 in) shell fragments.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It is made up of titanium plates with thicknesses varying from 0.5 to 1.5 inches (13 to 38 mm) determined by a study of likely trajectories and deflection angles.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The armor makes up almost six percent of the A-10's empty weight.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Any interior surface of the tub directly exposed to the pilot is covered by a multi-layer nylon spall shield to protect against shell fragmentation.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The front windscreen and canopy are resistant to small arms fire.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Despite this, Campbell's A-10 flew for nearly an hour and landed safely.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 was intended to fly from forward air bases and semi-prepared runways where foreign object damage to an aircraft's engines is normally a high risk.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The unusual location of the General Electric TF34-GE-100 turbofan engines decreases ingestion risk and also allows the engines to run while the aircraft is serviced and rearmed by ground crews, reducing turn-around time.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The wings are also mounted closer to the ground, simplifying servicing and rearming operations.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The heavy engines require strong support: four bolts connect the engine pylons to the airframe.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The engines' high 6:1 bypass ratio contributes to a relatively small infrared signature, and their position directs exhaust over the tailplanes further shielding it from detection by infrared homing surface-to-air missiles (SAM).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] To reduce the likelihood of damage to the fuel system, all four fuel tanks are located near the aircraft's center and are separated from the fuselage; projectiles would need to penetrate the aircraft's skin before reaching a fuel tank's outer skin.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Compromised fuel transfer lines self-seal; if damage exceeds a tank's self-sealing capabilities, check valves prevent fuel from flowing into a compromised tank.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Most fuel system components are inside the tanks so component failure will not lead to fuel loss.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The refueling system is also purged after use.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Reticulated polyurethane foam lines both the inner and outer sides of the fuel tanks, retaining debris and restricting fuel spillage in the event of damage.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The engines are shielded from the rest of the airframe by firewalls and fire extinguishing equipment.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] If all four main tanks were lost, two self-sealing sump tanks contain fuel for 230 miles (370 km) of flight.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10's primary built-in weapon is the 30×173 mm GAU-8/A Avenger autocannon made by General Electric.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] One of the most powerful aircraft cannons ever flown, the GAU-8 is a hydraulically driven seven-barrel rotary cannon designed for the anti-tank role with a high rate of fire.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The original design could be switched by the pilot to 2,100 or 4,200 depleted uranium armor-piercing shells per minute; this was later changed to a fixed rate of 3,900 rounds per minute.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The cannon takes about a half second to spin up to its maximum rate of fire, firing 50 rounds during the first second, and 65 or 70 rounds per second thereafter.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It is accurate enough to place 80 percent of its shots within a 40-foot (12.4 m) diameter circle from 4,000 feet (1,220 m) while in flight.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The GAU-8 is optimized for a slant range of 4,000 feet (1,220 m) with the A-10 in a 30-degree dive.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The aircraft's fuselage was designed around the cannon.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The GAU-8 is mounted slightly to the port side; the barrel in the firing location is on the starboard side so it is aligned with the aircraft's centerline.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The gun's 5-foot, 11.5-inch (1.816 m) ammunition drum can hold up to 1,350 rounds of 30 mm ammunition, but generally holds 1,174 rounds.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] To protect the rounds from enemy fire, armor plates of differing thicknesses between the aircraft skin and the drum are designed to detonate incoming shells.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 commonly carries the AGM-65 Maverick air-to-surface missile.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Targeted via electro-optical (TV-guided) or infrared systems, the Maverick can hit targets much farther away than the cannon, and thus incur less risk from anti-aircraft systems.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During Desert Storm, in the absence of dedicated forward-looking infrared (FLIR) cameras for night vision, the Maverick's infrared camera was used for night missions as a "poor man's FLIR".
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Other weapons include cluster bombs and Hydra 70 rocket pods.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 is equipped to carry GPS- and laser-guided bombs, such as the GBU-39 Small Diameter Bomb, Paveway series bombs, Joint Direct Attack Munitions (JDAM), Wind Corrected Munitions Dispenser and AGM-154 Joint Standoff Weapon glide bombs.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s usually fly with an ALQ-131 Electronic countermeasures (ECM) pod under one wing and two AIM-9 Sidewinder air-to-air missiles for self-defense under the other wing.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Aircraft camouflage is used to make the A-10 more difficult to see as it flies low to the ground at subsonic speeds.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Many types of paint schemes have been tried.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] These have included a "peanut scheme" of sand, yellow, and field drab; black and white colors for winter operations; and a tan, green, and brown mixed pattern.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The most common Cold War-era scheme was the European I woodland camouflage, whose dark green, medium green, and dark gray was meant to blend in with the typical European forest terrain.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It reflected the assumption that the threat from hostile fighter aircraft outweighed that from ground fire.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] After the 1991 Gulf War, the threat from ground fire was deemed more pressing than the air-to-air threat, leading to the "Compass Ghost" scheme with darker gray on top and a lighter gray on the underside of the aircraft.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Many A-10s also had a false canopy painted in dark gray on the underside of the aircraft, just behind the gun.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] This form of automimicry is an attempt to confuse the enemy as to aircraft attitude and maneuver direction.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Many A-10s feature nose art, such as shark mouth or warthog head features.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The first unit to receive the A-10 was the 355th Tactical Training Wing, based at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base, Arizona, in March 1976.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The first unit to achieve initial operating capability was the 354th Tactical Fighter Wing at Myrtle Beach Air Force Base, South Carolina, in October 1977.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10 deployments followed at bases both at home and abroad, including England AFB, Louisiana; Eielson AFB, Alaska; Osan Air Base, South Korea; and RAF Bentwaters/RAF Woodbridge, England.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The 81st TFW of RAF Bentwaters/RAF Woodbridge operated rotating detachments of A-10s at four bases in Germany known as Forward Operating Locations (FOLs): Leipheim, Sembach Air Base, Nörvenich Air Base, and RAF Ahlhorn.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s were initially an unwelcome addition to many in the USAF; most pilots did not want to switch to it as fighter pilots traditionally favored speed and appearance.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 1987, many A-10s were shifted to the forward air control (FAC) role and redesignated *OA-10*.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In the FAC role, the OA-10 is typically equipped with up to six pods of 2.75-inch (70 mm) Hydra rockets, usually with smoke or white phosphorus warheads used for target marking.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] OA-10s are physically unchanged and remain fully combat capable despite the redesignation.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The 23rd TFW's A-10s were deployed to Bridgetown, Barbados, during Operation Urgent Fury, the 1983 American Invasion of Grenada.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Marine Corps landings on the island of Carriacou in late October 1983, but did not fire weapons as no resistance was met.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 was used in combat for the first time during the Gulf War in 1991, with 132 being deployed.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s shot down two Iraqi helicopters with the GAU-8 cannon.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The first of these was shot down by Captain Robert Swain over Kuwait on 6 February 1991 for the A-10's first air-to-air victory.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Four A-10s were shot down during the war by surface-to-air missiles and eleven A-10s were hit by anti-air artillery rounds.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Another two battle-damaged A-10s and OA-10As returned to base and were written off.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Some sustained additional damage in crash landings.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] At the beginning of the war, A-10s flew missions against the Iraqi Republican Guard, but due to heavy attrition, from 15 February they were restricted to within 20 nautical miles (37 km) of the southern border.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s also flew missions hunting Iraqi Scud missiles.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 had a mission capable rate of 95.7 percent, flew 8,100 sorties, and launched 90 percent of the AGM-65 Maverick missiles fired in the conflict.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Shortly after the Gulf War, the USAF abandoned the idea of replacing the A-10 with a CAS version of the F-16.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s fired approximately 10,000 30 mm rounds in Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1994–95.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Following the seizure of heavy weapons by Bosnian Serbs from a warehouse in Ilidža, multiple sorties were launched to locate and destroy the captured equipment.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 5 August 1994, two A-10s located and strafed an anti-tank vehicle.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Afterward, the Serbs agreed to return the remaining heavy weapons.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In August 1995, NATO launched an offensive called Operation Deliberate Force.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s flew CAS missions, attacking Bosnian Serb artillery and positions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In late September, A-10s began flying patrols again.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s returned to the Balkan region as part of Operation Allied Force in Kosovo beginning in March 1999.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In March 1999, A-10s escorted and supported search and rescue helicopters in finding a downed F-117 pilot.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10s were deployed to support search and rescue missions, but gradually received more ground attack missions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10's first successful attack in Operation Allied Force happened on 6 April 1999; A-10s remained in action until the end of combat in June 1999.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Two A-10s were hit and damaged by enemy missiles over Kosovo during the campaign.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] One was hit on 2 May and had to make an emergency landing at Skopje International Airport while another was hit and lightly damaged on 11 May.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan, A-10s did not initially take part.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Beginning in March 2002, A-10 squadrons were deployed to Pakistan and Bagram Air Base, Afghanistan for the campaign against Taliban and Al-Qaeda, known as Operation Anaconda.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Afterward, they remained in-country, fighting Taliban and Al Qaeda remnants.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Operation Iraqi Freedom began on 20 March 2003.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Sixty OA-10/A-10s took part in early combat.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] United States Air Forces Central Command issued *Operation Iraqi Freedom: By the Numbers*, a declassified report about the aerial campaign in the conflict on 30 April 2003.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] During the initial invasion of Iraq, A-10s had a mission capable rate of 85 percent and fired 311,597 rounds of 30 mm ammunition.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The type also flew 32 missions to airdrop propaganda leaflets.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A single A-10 was shot down near Baghdad International Airport by Iraqi fire late in the campaign.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In September 2007, the A-10C with the Precision Engagement Upgrade reached initial operating capability.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10C first deployed to Iraq in 2007 with the 104th Fighter Squadron of the Maryland Air National Guard.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10C's digital avionics and communications systems greatly reduced the time to acquire and attack CAS targets.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10s flew 32 percent of combat sorties in Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In the first half of 2013, they flew 11,189 sorties in Afghanistan.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] From the start of 2006 to October 2013, A-10s conducted 19 percent of CAS missions in Iraq and Afghanistan, more than the F-15E Strike Eagle and Rockwell B-1B Lancer, but less than the 33 percent flown by F-16s.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In March 2011, six A-10s were deployed as part of Operation Odyssey Dawn, the coalition intervention in Libya.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] They participated in attacks on Libyan ground forces there.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF 122nd Fighter Wing revealed it would deploy to the Middle East in October 2014 with 12 A-10s.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Although the deployment had been planned a year in advance in a support role, the timing coincided with the ongoing Operation Inherent Resolve against ISIL militants.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] From mid-November, U.S. commanders began sending A-10s to hit IS targets in central and northwestern Iraq on an almost daily basis.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Over a two-month period, A-10s flew 11 percent of all USAF sorties since the start of operations in August 2014.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 was involved in the killing of 35 Afghan civilians from 2010 to 2015, more than any other U.S. military aircraft and also involved in killing ten U.S. troops in friendly fire over four incidents between 2001 and 2015.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] These incidents have been assessed as "inconclusive and statistically insignificant" in terms of the plane's capability.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 19 January 2018, 12 A-10s from the 303d Expeditionary Fighter Squadron were deployed to Kandahar Airfield, Afghanistan, to provide CAS, marking the first time in more than three years A-10s had been deployed to Afghanistan.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 29 November and 3 December 2024, USAF A-10s were used against targets in Syria to defend US forces in eastern Syria as part of the ongoing Syrian civil war.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF said the strikes destroyed vehicles, mortars, and a T-64 tank.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Concurrent with the fall of the Assad regime on 8 December, A-10s participated alongside B-52s and F-15Es in what the USAF said were "dozens" of airstrikes against over 75 ISIS targets.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The strikes were intended to prevent ISIS from benefitting from the political upheaval in Syria.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 29 March 2025, "several" A-10s from the 124th Fighter Wing were deployed to the Middle East as part of the continued conflict with Houthi forces in Yemen.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Central Command stated that A-10s were employed during the first 24 hours of 2026 Iran war.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Top US general Dan Caine later said that A-10s were used for "hunting and killing fast-attack watercraft" in the Hormuz Strait during the war.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 3 April 2026, a USAF A-10 was shot down in the Persian Gulf by Iranian air defences amid a combat search and rescue mission for a downed F-15E crewman (WSO).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 made it to Kuwaiti airspace where the pilot ejected and was rescued while the A-10 crashed.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10's future remains a subject of debate.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2007, the USAF expected it to remain in service until 2028 and possibly later, when it would likely be replaced by the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Director of the Straus Military Reform Project of the Project On Government Oversight Winslow Wheeler, a critic of this plan, said that replacing the A-10 with the F-35 would be a "giant leap backwards" given the A-10's performance and the F-35's high costs.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2012, the USAF considered the F-35B STOVL variant as a replacement CAS aircraft, but concluded that it could not generate sufficient sorties.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In August 2013, Congress and the USAF examined various proposals, including the F-35 and the MQ-9 Reaper unmanned aerial vehicle filling the A-10's role.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Proponents state that the A-10's armor and cannon are superior to aircraft such as the F-35 for ground attack, that guided munitions could be jammed, and that ground commanders commonly request A-10 support.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In the USAF's FY 2015 budget, the service considered retiring the A-10 and other single-mission aircraft, prioritizing multi-mission aircraft; cutting a whole fleet and its infrastructure was seen as the only method for major savings.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Army had expressed interest in obtaining some A-10s were the USAF to retire them, but later stated there was "no chance" of that happening.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF stated that retirement would save $3.7 billion from 2015 to 2019.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Guided munitions allow more aircraft to perform CAS duties and reduce the need for specialized aircraft; since 2001, multirole aircraft and bombers have performed 80 percent of operational CAS missions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The USAF also said that the A-10 was increasingly vulnerable to modern anti-aircraft weapons, but the Army replied that it had proved invaluable due to its versatile weapons loads, psychological impact, and limited logistics needs.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In January 2015, USAF officials told lawmakers that it would take 15 years to fully develop a new attack aircraft to replace the A-10; that year General Herbert J.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Carlisle, the head of Air Combat Command, stated that a follow-on weapon system for the A-10 may need development.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] It planned for F-16s and F-15Es to initially take up CAS sorties, and later by the F-35A once sufficient numbers become operationally available over the next decade.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In July 2015, Boeing held initial discussions on the prospects of selling retired or stored A-10s in near-flyaway condition to international customers.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] However, the USAF stated that it would not permit any to be sold.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Plans to develop a replacement aircraft were announced by the US Air Combat Command in August 2015.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2016, the USAF began studying future CAS aircraft to succeed the A-10 in low-intensity "permissive conflicts" like counterterrorism and regional stability operations, noting the F-35 to be too expensive to operate in day-to-day roles.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In January 2016, the USAF was "indefinitely freezing" plans to retire the A-10.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Beyond congressional opposition, its use in anti-ISIS operations, deployments to Eastern Europe as a response to Russia's military intervention in Ukraine, and reevaluation of F-35 numbers necessitated its retention.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In February 2016, the USAF deferred the final retirement date until 2022 after F-35s replace it on a squadron-by-squadron basis.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In October 2016, the USAF Materiel Command brought the depot maintenance line back to full capacity in preparation for re-winging the fleet.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In June 2017, it was announced that the A-10 is retained indefinitely.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine led to some observers pushing for A-10s to be loaned to Ukraine while critics noted the diplomatic and tactical complications involved.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In an interview in December 2022, Ukrainian Defense Minister Oleksii Reznikov said that in late March he asked the US Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin for 100 surplus A-10s, noting their value against Russian tank columns.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] However, Austin reportedly told Minister Reznikov that the plan was "impossible", and that the "old-fashioned and slow" A-10 would be a "squeaky target" for Russian air defenses.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] With Russo-Ukrainian war's rapid development of drone warfare, the A-10's effectiveness in the anti-drone screening role could potentially extend its service life.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Due to opposition from Congress, the USAF has failed to retire the A-10 for many years.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] However, the Air Force's plan to divest 21 A-10s gained congressional approval in the 2023 National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The retired A-10s at Fort Wayne will be replaced by an equal number of F-16s.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The 2024 NDAA is expected to retire an additional 42 aircraft, with Air Force Chief of Staff Charles Brown expecting all A-10s to be retired by 2028 or 2029.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] However, Congress would pause further cuts unless the Air Force demonstrates how other aircraft can fulfill the Close Air Support missions currently undertaken by the A-10.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] According to Dan Grazier from Project on Government Oversight, the Air Force is ill-prepared for this transition because it requires no Close Air Support training for its F-35 pilots, despite the F-35 being advertised as the main replacement for the A-10.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In April 2026 US Secretary of the Air Force Troy Meink announced that the A-10 retirement would be delayed until 2030 amid the 2026 Iran War.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] On 25 March 2010, an A-10 conducted the first flight of an aircraft with all engines powered by a biofuel blend comprising a 1:1 blend of JP-8 and Camelina-based fuel.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] ATJ is the third alternative fuel to be evaluated by the USAF as a replacement for the petroleum-derived JP-8 fuel.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Previous types were synthetic paraffinic kerosene derived from coal and natural gas and a bio-mass fuel derived from plant oils and animal fats known as Hydroprocessed Renewable Jet.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2011, the National Science Foundation granted $11 million to modify an A-10 for weather research for CIRPAS at the U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Naval Postgraduate School and in collaboration with scientists from the South Dakota School of Mines & Technology (SDSM&T), replacing SDSM&T's retired North American T-28 Trojan.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2018, this plan was found to be too risky due to the costly modifications required, thus the program was canceled.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Single-seat close air support, ground-attack production version.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10As used for airborne forward air control.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Two-seat experimental prototype, for work at night and in bad weather.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The one YA-10B prototype was converted from an A-10A.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] A-10As updated under the incremental Precision Engagement (PE) program.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The PCAS program eventually dropped the idea of using an optionally manned A-10.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 would have its military engines, avionics, and oxygen system replaced by civilian versions.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] , and the GAU-8 Avenger would be replaced with ballast or scientific instruments.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] Project canceled after partial modification of a single A-10C.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] The A-10 has been flown exclusively by the United States Air Force and its Air Reserve components, the Air Force Reserve Command (AFRC) and the Air National Guard (ANG).
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] As of 2017, 282 A-10C aircraft are reported as operational, divided as follows: 141 USAF, 55 AFRC, 86 ANG.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p01] In 2025, there were 270 A-10Cs in service with the USAF.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] On 8 December 1988, an A-10A of the U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] Air Forces in Europe crashed into a residential area in the city of Remscheid, West Germany.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The aircraft crashed into the upper floor of an apartment complex.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The pilot and six other people were killed.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] Fifty others were injured, many of them seriously.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The cause of the accident was attributed to spatial disorientation, after both the mishap aircraft and its flight lead encountered difficult and adverse weather conditions for visual flying.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The number of cancer cases in the vicinity of the accident rose disproportionately in the years after, raising the possibility that the aircraft may have been loaded with ammunition containing depleted uranium, contrary to U.S. statements.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] Air Force A-10 from Davis–Monthan Air Force Base piloted by Captain Craig D.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] Button inexplicably flew hundreds of miles off-course without radio contact.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The pilot appeared to maneuver purposefully and did not attempt to eject before the crash.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] His death is regarded as a suicide because no other hypothesis explains the events.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The incident caused widespread public speculation about Button's intentions and whereabouts until the crash site was found three weeks later at the 12,500 ft mark on Gold Dust Peak, a remote mountain roughly 15 miles southwest of Vail, Colorado.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The aircraft carried live bombs which have not been recovered.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] On 28 March 2003, British Lance-Corporal of Horse Matty Hull was killed by a U.S.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] A-10 along with five others wounded in the 190th Fighter Squadron, Blues and Royals friendly fire incident.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The A-10 Thunderbolt II received its popular nickname "Warthog" from the pilots and crews of the USAF attack squadrons who flew and maintained it.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The A-10 is the last of Republic's jet attack aircraft to serve with the USAF.
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The Republic F-84 Thunderjet was nicknamed the "Hog", F-84F Thunderstreak nicknamed "Superhog", and the Republic F-105 Thunderchief tagged "Ultra Hog".
[src:armour/a-10-thunderbolt-ii-p02] The saying *Go Ugly Early* has been associated with the aircraft for calling in the A-10 early to support troops in ground combat.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] The **A2 Helmet** is a standard issued combat helmet of the Vietnam People's Army introduced in 2010.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] Its main purpose is protection during training exercises and combat drills rather than actual combat scenarios.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] Up until 2014, a majority of the Vietnam People's Army were still using Pith Helmets.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] These Pith Helmets also saw significant use during the Vietnam War.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] Around 2014, the army began to mass-produce these A2 Helmets as a cost-effective replacement for older equipment in the army.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] They are now a standard issued helmet commonly used across all branches of the army.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] The design of the helmet is similar to the PASGT without any Kevlar materials.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] The helmet is made of Polyamide Plastic and is designed with double-layered plastic cladding that are overlapped, foam lining, and mesh fabric on the inside.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] Due to its non-bulletproof design, its mainly used as a helmet for training exercises and it can protect the user against explosive fragments.
[src:armour/a2-helmet] They are commonly clothed with camouflage, or the camouflaged is directly painted on.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The **Adrian helmet** (French: *Casque Adrian*) is a combat helmet designed by Louis Adrian for the French Army during World War I.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Its original version, the M15, was the first standard helmet of the French Army and was designed when millions of French troops were engaged in trench warfare, and head wounds from falling shrapnel generated by indirect fire became a frequent cause of battlefield casualties.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Introduced in 1915, it was the first modern steel helmet and it served as the basic helmet of many armies well into the 1930s.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Initially issued to infantry soldiers, in modified form they were also issued to cavalry and tank crews.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] A subsequent version, the M26, was used during World War II.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] At the outbreak of World War I in August 1914, soldiers in the French Army wore the standard kepi cap, which provided no protection against injury.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The early stages of trench warfare proved that even basic protection of the head would result in a significantly lower mortality rate among front-line soldiers.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] By the beginning of 1915, a rudimentary steel skull-cap (*calotte métallique*, *cervelière*) was being issued to be worn under the kepi.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Consequently, the French staff ordered development of a metal helmet that could protect soldiers from the shrapnel of exploding artillery shells.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Intendant-General Louis Adrian designed a helmet which was adopted by the French military and named after him.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Since soldiers in trenches were also vulnerable to shrapnel exploding above their heads, a deflector crest was added along the helmet's axis.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Branch insignia in the form of a flaming grenade for line infantry and cavalry, a bugle horn for chasseurs, flaming grenade and crossed cannon for artillery, an anchor for colonial troops and a crescent for North African units was attached to the front.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Contrary to common misconception, the Adrian helmet, and other World War I helmets, were not designed to protect the wearer from direct impact by rifle or machine gun cartridges, but shrapnel from indirect fire.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The helmet adopted by the army was made of mild steel and weighed only 0.765 kg (1 lb 11.0 oz), which made it lighter and less protective than the contemporary British Brodie helmet and the German *Stahlhelm*.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Orders were placed for the helmets in the spring of 1915, which started being issued by July.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] By September, all frontline troops in France were issued the helmet.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The helmet was surprisingly complex to produce, with seventy stages involved in its production, not including those required to prepare the metal.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The slot for the badges and the distinctive crest took additional time to manufacture, while also adding a hundred grams of weight.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] However, the helmet was deliberately designed this way to evoke the artistic style of the highly popular military artist Édouard Detaille, which helped raise the morale of the troops.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Indeed French troops identified closely with their helmets.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The helmet's light weight was also better suited to France's emphasis on mobility and was easier for soldiers to wear for extended periods.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] In addition to the helmet, a set of armored "epaulets" were also developed by Adrian and issued to defend against shrapnel and air-dropped darts, although they were not in common use.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] From late 1915, a cloth cover for the helmet was issued, in khaki or light blue, to prevent reflection.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] However, it was found that if the helmet was pierced by shell splinters, pieces of dirty cloth were carried into the wound, which increased the risk of infection.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Consequently, in mid-1916 an order was issued that the covers should be discarded.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] By the end of World War I, the Adrian had been issued to almost all infantry units fighting with the French Army.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] It was also used by some of the American divisions fighting in France, including the African-American 369th Infantry Regiment, commonly known as the Harlem Hellfighters, and the Polish forces of Haller's Blue Army.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The French *Gendarmerie mobile* adopted a dark blue version in 1926, and continued to wear it into the 1960s, well after the regular army had discarded it.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] In December 1915, Winston Churchill (later to become Prime Minister of the United Kingdom from 1940 to 1945), while serving as a major with the British Army's Grenadier Guards, was presented with an Adrian helmet by the French General Émile Fayolle.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] He is seen wearing it in photographs and in a portrait painted by Sir John Lavery.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The helmet proved to be fairly effective against shrapnel and while complex to manufacture (see details above) it was relatively inexpensive.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] As a consequence, more than twenty million Adrian helmets were produced.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] However, because the new steel helmets offered little protection against bullets, they were reportedly often among the first pieces of equipment to be abandoned by soldiers on the battlefield.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] It was also discovered that the badge placed on the front of helmets impaired the strength of the helmet because of the two slots required.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] This perceived weakness made several armies remove their national insignia altogether.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Early helmets were painted "horizon-blue" (light blue-grey) for French troops and khaki for colonial forces.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Those made after 1935 are usually painted khaki, reflecting the French army movement to a more camouflaged uniform in the 1930s.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] In 1926, the Adrian helmet was modified by being constructed of stronger steel and simplified by having the main part of the helmet stamped from one piece of metal, and therefore without the joining rim around the helmet that characterizes the M15.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The large ventilation hole under the comb, which had been a weak point of the old design, was also replaced with a series of small holes.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The M26 helmet continued in use with the French Army until after World War II, and was also used by the French police up to the 1970s.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] During the interwar period Belgium began to produce their own domestically made M26 Adrians and exported them around the globe.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] These helmets can be distinguished from their French counterparts, because they have a slightly different comb and a wider rim.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] In other countries the Adrian-type helmets were also in use with the firefighting units, railway guards or marine infantry (e.g.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] Adrian helmets are still prized by collectors today.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] In 1940, Mexico began to produce M26 helmets locally after shipments from France stopped due to the German occupation.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] A crestless version was produced in small numbers as well.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The last country to replace the adrian helmets was Thailand.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The Thai had adopted the Adrian helmet in the interwar period and issued them until the 70s, when more modern and affordable helmets such as the American M1 replaced the French helmet.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] A 2020 study published by *PLOS One* found that the Adrian helmet outperformed the Advanced Combat Helmet, which was deployed almost a century later, in protection against overhead blasts waves.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] It also surpassed the Stahlhelm and Brodie helmets.
[src:armour/adrian-helmet] The researchers believed the crest, a feature unique to the Adrian helmet, might be the cause.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The **Advanced Combat Helmet** (**ACH**) is the United States Army's current combat helmet, used since the early 2000s.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Army Special Operations Command, and the U.S.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Army Research Laboratory to be the next generation of protective combat helmets for use by the American ground forces.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH is derived from the Modular Integrated Communications Helmet (MICH).
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH is currently in the process of being phased out and replaced by the Enhanced Combat Helmet (ECH), an improvement upon the ACH derived from its design; however, both the ACH and the newer ECH are being replaced by the Integrated Head Protection System (IHPS).
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The Advanced Combat Helmet was first fielded beginning in 2003 in limited numbers to eventually replace the PASGT helmet.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] In 2006, 102,000 helmets were ordered from ArmorSource, of which 99,000 were delivered when the contract was fulfilled and properly closed.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] In 2007, the Army introduced a ballistic "nape pad" that attaches to the ACH's rear suspension system.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Of these, 430,000 were to be issued in the Rapid Fielding Initiative (RFI).
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Beginning in 2008, the Army's Program Executive Office Soldier outfitted soldiers of the 101st Airborne Division and 4th Infantry Division bound for Iraq with helmet-mounted sensors designed to gather data on head injuries (or traumatic brain injuries) caused during IED detonations.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The data collected will help in the designing of improvements for the ACH's suspension and chin strap systems.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] In May 2009, 55,000 of these were in storage and 44,000 were in use by U.S.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The 44,000 helmets in use by service members were recalled by the U.S.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Army in May 2010 due to potentially defective materials being used.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Eventually, the contractor agreed to pay a $3 million fine, without admitting to any wrongdoing by the contractor.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] In May 2009, 34,218 ACHs made by Gentex Corporation were recalled.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Certain screws attaching the chinstrap and other parts to the helmet did not conform to specifications in the contract.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The screws failed ballistics tests at extreme temperatures.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Gentex alleges its subcontractor had fabricated the compliance certificates for the screws.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Beginning in late 2009, an OEF-CP (MultiCam) helmet cover for the Advanced Combat Helmet was issued to soldiers deployed in Afghanistan.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] On 7 March 2016, Armorsource LLC agreed to pay $3 million to settle False Claims Act allegations.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Revision was awarded a contract for the ACH II contract.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH and Lightweight Helmet (LWH) will eventually be replaced by the Enhanced Combat Helmet and Integrated Head Protection System (IHPS).
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The shape of the ACH is virtually identical to the MICH TC-2000.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] Compared to the PASGT helmet, the front brow is eliminated to improve upwards visibility and allow easier mounting of night-vision goggle brackets.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The side brim has been raised to the point that the entire lower brim of the helmet is "flat" compared to the PASGT which curves upwards at the back.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] This is to allow greater compatibility with communications headsets and improve hearing when headsets are not used.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH uses ballistic fiber such as kevlar and twaron.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] In 2007, the Army developed and introduced a ballistic "nape pad" that attaches to the ACH's rear suspension system and coincided with the introduction of the Improved Outer Tactical Vest (IOTV).
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The pad reduces soldier deaths from fragmentation wounds to the neck and lower head.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH comes from the factory painted sand tan, grey, black, or forest green (officially designated as Camouflage Green 383).
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] It is often worn with cloth helmet covers in various camouflage patterns including Universal Camouflage Pattern, Operational Camouflage Pattern, and the USAF's ABU pattern.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The helmet cover may also have small squares of infrared reflective material on the sides, top, and rear which illuminate when viewed through thermal imaging, allowing for friend or foe identification during combat.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The helmet can also be fitted with an elastic band with a pair of glow in the dark "cat eye" patches, similar to those seen on the older PASGT helmet.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] A pair of Cordura straps can be mounted on the rear of the helmet to aid in the retention of protective goggles.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH is also commonly seen with a mounting bracket on the front for night vision devices.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] These brackets often come in one of two designs; a tan or black "tombstone" shape that attaches to the helmet with a single screw through the center, or a larger tan diamond-shaped mount that attaches with three screws, one at each corner.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH can also be fitted with Picatinny rails on the sides of the helmet for mounting flashlights or digital cameras.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The **Lightweight Advanced Combat Helmet Generation II** (**LW-ACH Gen II**) weighs up to one pound less than the original ACH while offering the same ballistic protection.
[src:armour/advanced-combat-helmet] The ACH Gen II achieved an average of 22% in weight reduction from legacy helmets.
[src:armour/armour] A second use of the term *armour* describes armoured forces, armoured weapons, and their role in combat.
[src:armour/armour] After the development of armoured warfare, tanks and mechanised infantry and their combat formations came to be referred to collectively as "armour".
[src:armour/armour] The word "armour" began to appear in the Middle Ages as a derivative of Old French.
[src:armour/armour] It is dated from 1297 as a "mail, defensive covering worn in combat".
[src:armour/armour] The word originates from the Old French *armure*, itself derived from the Latin *armatura* meaning "arms and/or equipment", with the root *armare* meaning "arms or gear".
[src:armour/armour] Armour has been used throughout recorded history.
[src:armour/armour] It has been made from a variety of materials, beginning with the use of leathers or fabrics as protection and evolving through chain mail and metal plate into today's modern composites.
[src:armour/armour] For much of military history the manufacture of metal personal armour has dominated the technology and employment of armour.
[src:armour/armour] Armour drove the development of many important technologies of the Ancient World, including wood lamination, mining, metal refining, vehicle manufacture, leather processing, and later decorative metal working.
[src:armour/armour] Its production was influential in the Industrial Revolution, and furthered commercial development of metallurgy and engineering.
[src:armour/armour] Armour was also an important factor in the development of firearms, which in turn revolutionised warfare.
[src:armour/armour] Significant factors in the development of armour include the economic and technological necessities of its production.
[src:armour/armour] For instance, plate armour became widespread in Medieval Europe when water-powered trip hammers made the forming of plates faster and cheaper.
[src:armour/armour] At times the development of armour has paralleled the development of increasingly effective weaponry on the battlefield, with armourers seeking to create better protection without sacrificing mobility.
[src:armour/armour] A well known example in Europe of Asian armour are the many types of armour used by warriors of Feudal Japan for hundreds of years up to the 19th century.
[src:armour/armour] The first record of body armour in history was found on the Stele of Vultures in ancient Sumer in today's south Iraq, and various forms of scale mail can be seen in surviving records from the New Kingdom of Egypt, Zhou dynasty China, and dynastic India.
[src:armour/armour] Cuirasses and helmets were manufactured in Japan as early as the 4th century.
[src:armour/armour] *Tankō*, worn by foot soldiers and *keikō*, worn by horsemen were both pre-samurai types of early Japanese armour constructed from iron plates connected together by leather thongs.
[src:armour/armour] Japanese lamellar armour (*keiko*) passed through Korea and reached Japan around the 5th century.
[src:armour/armour] These early Japanese lamellar armours took the form of a sleeveless jacket, leggings and a helmet.
[src:armour/armour] Armour did not always cover all of the body; sometimes no more than a helmet and leg plates were worn.
[src:armour/armour] The rest of the body was generally protected by means of a large shield.
[src:armour/armour] An example of armies equipping their troops in this fashion were the Aztecs (13th to 15th century CE).
[src:armour/armour] The Chinese, during that time used partial plates for "important" body parts instead of covering their whole body since too much plate armour hinders their martial arts movement.
[src:armour/armour] The other body parts were covered in cloth, leather, lamellar, or mountain pattern armour.
[src:armour/armour] Mail, sometimes called "chainmail", made of interlocking iron rings is believed to have first appeared some time after 300 BC.
[src:armour/armour] Its invention is credited to the Celts; the Romans are thought to have adopted their design.
[src:armour/armour] Gradually, small additional plates or discs of iron were added to the mail to protect vulnerable areas.
[src:armour/armour] Hardened leather and splinted construction were used for arm and leg pieces.
[src:armour/armour] The coat of plates was developed, an armour made of large plates sewn inside a textile or leather coat.
[src:armour/armour] Early plate in Italy, and elsewhere in the 13th–15th century, were made of iron.
[src:armour/armour] Iron armour could be carburised or case hardened to give a surface of harder steel.
[src:armour/armour] Plate armour became cheaper than mail by the 15th century as it required much less labour and labour had become much more expensive after the Black Death, though it did require larger furnaces to produce larger blooms.
[src:armour/armour] Mail continued to be used to protect those joints which could not be adequately protected by plate, such as the armpit, crook of the elbow and groin.
[src:armour/armour] Another advantage of plate was that a lance rest could be fitted to the breast plate.
[src:armour/armour] The small skull cap evolved into a bigger true helmet, the bascinet, as it was lengthened downward to protect the back of the neck and the sides of the head.
[src:armour/armour] Additionally, several new forms of fully enclosed helmets were introduced in the late 14th century.
[src:armour/armour] Probably the most recognised style of armour in the world became the plate armour associated with the knights of the European Late Middle Ages, but continuing to the early 17th century Baroque period in all European countries.
[src:armour/armour] By 1400, the full harness of plate armour had been developed in armouries of Lombardy.
[src:armour/armour] Heavy cavalry dominated the battlefield for centuries in part because of their armour.
[src:armour/armour] In the early 15th century, advances in weaponry allowed infantry to defeat armoured knights on the battlefield.
[src:armour/armour] The quality of the metal used in armour deteriorated as armies became bigger and armour was made thicker, necessitating breeding of larger cavalry horses.
[src:armour/armour] If during the 14–15th centuries armour seldom weighed more than 15 kg, then by the late 16th century it weighed 25 kg.
[src:armour/armour] The increasing weight and thickness of late 16th century armour therefore gave substantial resistance.
[src:armour/armour] In the early years of low velocity firearms, full suits of armour, or breast plates actually stopped bullets fired from a modest distance.
[src:armour/armour] Crossbow bolts, if still in use, would seldom penetrate good plate, nor would any bullet unless fired from close range.
[src:armour/armour] In effect, rather than making plate armour obsolete, the use of firearms stimulated the development of plate armour into its later stages.
[src:armour/armour] For most of that period, it allowed horsemen to fight while being the targets of defending arquebusiers without being easily killed.
[src:armour/armour] Full suits of armour were actually worn by generals and princely commanders right up to the second decade of the 18th century.
[src:armour/armour] It was the only way they could be mounted and survey the overall battlefield with safety from distant musket fire.
[src:armour/armour] The horse was afforded protection from lances and infantry weapons by steel plate barding.
[src:armour/armour] This gave the horse protection and enhanced the visual impression of a mounted knight.
[src:armour/armour] Late in the era, elaborate barding was used in parade armour.
[src:armour/armour] Gradually, starting in the mid-16th century, one plate element after another was discarded to save weight for foot soldiers.
[src:armour/armour] Back and breast plates continued to be used throughout the entire period of the 18th century and through Napoleonic times, in many European heavy cavalry units, until the early 20th century.
[src:armour/armour] From their introduction, muskets could pierce plate armour, so cavalry had to be far more mindful of the fire.
[src:armour/armour] In Japan, armour continued to be used until the late 19th century, with the last major fighting in which armour was used, this occurred in 1868.
[src:armour/armour] Samurai armour had one last short lived use in 1877 during the Satsuma Rebellion.
[src:armour/armour] Though the age of the knight was over, armour continued to be used in many capacities.
[src:armour/armour] Soldiers in the American Civil War bought iron and steel vests from peddlers (both sides had considered but rejected body armour for standard issue).
[src:armour/armour] The effectiveness of the vests varied widely, some successfully deflected bullets and saved lives, but others were poorly made and resulted in tragedy for the soldiers.
[src:armour/armour] In any case the vests were abandoned by many soldiers due to their increased weight on long marches, as well as the stigma they got for being cowards from their fellow troops.
[src:armour/armour] At the start of World War I, thousands of the French Cuirassiers rode out to engage the German Cavalry.
[src:armour/armour] By that period, the shiny metallic cuirass was covered in a dark paint and a canvas wrap covered their elaborate Napoleonic style helmets, to help mitigate the sunlight being reflected off the surfaces, thereby alerting the enemy of their location.
[src:armour/armour] Their armour was only meant for protection against edged weapons such as bayonets, sabres, and lances.
[src:armour/armour] Cavalry had to be wary of repeating rifles, machine guns, and artillery, unlike the foot soldiers, who at least had a trench to give them some protection.
[src:armour/armour] Today, ballistic vests, also known as flak jackets, made of ballistic cloth (e.g. kevlar, dyneema, twaron, spectra etc.) and ceramic or metal plates are common among police officers, security guards, corrections officers and some branches of the military.
[src:armour/armour] The US Army has adopted Interceptor body armour, which uses Enhanced Small Arms Protective Inserts (ESAPIs) in the chest, sides, and back of the armour.
[src:armour/armour] Each plate is rated to stop a range of ammunition including 3 hits from a 7.62×51 NATO AP round at a range of 10 m (33 ft).
[src:armour/armour] Dragon Skin is another ballistic vest which is currently in testing with mixed results.
[src:armour/armour] As of 2019, it has been deemed too heavy, expensive, and unreliable, in comparison to more traditional plates, and it is outdated in protection compared to modern US IOTV armour, and even in testing was deemed a downgrade from the IBA.
[src:armour/armour] The British Armed Forces also have their own armour, known as Osprey.
[src:armour/armour] It is rated to the same general equivalent standard as the US counterpart, the Improved Outer Tactical Vest, and now the Soldier Plate Carrier System and Modular Tactical Vest.
[src:armour/armour] The Russian Armed Forces also have armour, known as the 6B43, all the way to 6B45, depending on variant.
[src:armour/armour] Their armour runs on the GOST system, which, due to regional conditions, has resulted in a technically higher protective level overall.
[src:armour/armour] The first modern production technology for armour plating was used by navies in the construction of the ironclad warship, reaching its pinnacle of development with the battleship.
[src:armour/armour] The first tanks were produced during World War I.
[src:armour/armour] Aerial armour has been used to protect pilots and aircraft systems since the First World War.
[src:armour/armour] In modern ground forces' usage, the meaning of armour has expanded to include the role of troops in combat.
[src:armour/armour] After the evolution of armoured warfare, mechanised infantry were mounted in armoured fighting vehicles and replaced light infantry in many situations.
[src:armour/armour] In modern armoured warfare, armoured units equipped with tanks and infantry fighting vehicles serve the historic role of heavy cavalry, light cavalry, and dragoons, and belong to the armoured branch of warfare.
[src:armour/armour] The first ironclad battleship, with iron armour over a wooden hull, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in 1859 prompting the British Royal Navy to build a counter.
[src:armour/armour] The following year they launched HMS *Warrior*, which was twice the size and had iron armour over an iron hull.
[src:armour/armour] After the first battle between two ironclads took place in 1862 during the American Civil War, it became clear that the ironclad had replaced the unarmoured line-of-battle ship as the most powerful warship afloat.
[src:armour/armour] Ironclads were designed for several roles, including as high seas battleships, coastal defence ships, and long-range cruisers.
[src:armour/armour] The rapid evolution of warship design in the late 19th century transformed the ironclad from a wooden-hulled vessel which carried sails to supplement its steam engines into the steel-built, turreted battleships and cruisers familiar in the 20th century.
[src:armour/armour] This change was pushed forward by the development of heavier naval guns (the ironclads of the 1880s carried some of the heaviest guns ever mounted at sea), more sophisticated steam engines, and advances in metallurgy which made steel shipbuilding possible.
[src:armour/armour] The rapid pace of change in the ironclad period meant that many ships were obsolete as soon as they were complete, and that naval tactics were in a state of flux.
[src:armour/armour] Many ironclads were built to make use of the ram or the torpedo, which a number of naval designers considered the crucial weapons of naval combat.
[src:armour/armour] There is no clear end to the ironclad period, but towards the end of the 1890s the term *ironclad* dropped out of use.
[src:armour/armour] New ships were increasingly constructed to a standard pattern and designated battleships or armoured cruisers.
[src:armour/armour] The most intensive use of armoured trains was during the Russian Civil War (1918–1920).
[src:armour/armour] Ancient siege engines were usually protected by wooden armour, often covered with wet hides or thin metal to prevent being easily burned.
[src:armour/armour] Medieval war wagons were horse-drawn wagons that were similarly armoured.
[src:armour/armour] These contained guns or crossbowmen that could fire through gun-slits.
[src:armour/armour] The first modern armoured fighting vehicles were armoured cars, developed c.
[src:armour/armour] These started as ordinary wheeled motor-cars protected by iron shields, typically mounting a machine gun.
[src:armour/armour] During the First World War, the stalemate of trench warfare on the Western Front spurred the development of the tank.
[src:armour/armour] It was envisioned as an armoured machine that could advance under fire from enemy rifles and machine guns, and respond with its own heavy guns.
[src:armour/armour] It used caterpillar tracks to cross ground broken up by shellfire and trenches.
[src:armour/armour] With the development of effective anti-aircraft artillery in the period before the Second World War, military pilots, once the "knights of the air" during the First World War, became far more vulnerable to ground fire.
[src:armour/armour] As a response, armour plating was added to aircraft to protect aircrew and vulnerable areas such as engines and fuel tanks.
[src:armour/armour] Self-sealing fuel tanks functioned like armour in that they added protection but also increased weight and cost.
[src:armour/armour] Tank armour has progressed from the Second World War armour forms, now incorporating not only harder composites, but also reactive armour designed to defeat shaped charges.
[src:armour/armour] As a result of this, the main battle tank (MBT) conceived in the Cold War era can survive multiple rocket-propelled grenade strikes with minimal effect on the crew or the operation of the vehicle.
[src:armour/armour] The light tanks that were the last descendants of the light cavalry during the Second World War have almost completely disappeared from the world's militaries due to increased lethality of the weapons available to the vehicle-mounted infantry.
[src:armour/armour] The armoured personnel carrier (APC) was devised during the First World War.
[src:armour/armour] It allows the safe and rapid movement of infantry in a combat zone, minimising casualties and maximising mobility.
[src:armour/armour] APCs are fundamentally different from the previously used armoured half-tracks in that they offer a higher level of protection from artillery burst fragments, and greater mobility in more terrain types.
[src:armour/armour] The basic APC design was substantially expanded to an infantry fighting vehicle (IFV) when properties of an APC and a light tank were combined in one vehicle.
[src:armour/armour] Naval armour has fundamentally changed from the Second World War doctrine of thicker plating to defend against shells, bombs and torpedoes.
[src:armour/armour] Passive defence naval armour is limited to kevlar or steel (either single layer or as spaced armour) protecting particularly vital areas from the effects of nearby impacts.
[src:armour/armour] Since ships cannot carry enough armour to completely protect against anti-ship missiles, they depend more on defensive weapons destroying incoming missiles, or causing them to miss by confusing their guidance systems with electronic warfare.
[src:armour/armour] High-voltage transformer fire barriers are often required to defeat ballistics from small arms as well as projectiles from transformer bushings and lightning arresters, which form part of large electrical transformers, per NFPA 850.
[src:armour/armour] Combat drones use little to no vehicular armour as they are not crewed vessels, this results in them being lightweight and small in size.
[src:armour/armour] Body armour for war horses has been used since at least 2000 BC.
[src:armour/armour] Cloth, leather, and metal protection covered cavalry horses in ancient civilisations, including ancient Egypt, Assyria, Persia, and Rome.
[src:armour/armour] Some formed heavy cavalry units of armoured horses and riders used to attack infantry and mounted archers.
[src:armour/armour] Armour for horses is called *barding* (also spelled *bard* or *barb*) especially when used by European knights.
[src:armour/armour] During the late Middle Ages as armour protection for knights became more effective, their mounts became targets.
[src:armour/armour] This vulnerability was exploited by the Scots at the Battle of Bannockburn in the 14th century, when horses were killed by the infantry, and for the English at the Battle of Crécy in the same century where longbowmen shot horses and the then dismounted French knights were killed by heavy infantry.
[src:armour/armour] Barding developed as a response to such events.
[src:armour/armour] Examples of armour for horses could be found as far back as classical antiquity.
[src:armour/armour] Cataphracts, with scale armour for both rider and horse, are believed by many historians to have influenced the later European knights, via contact with the Byzantine Empire.
[src:armour/armour] Surviving period examples of barding are rare; however, complete sets are on display at the Philadelphia Museum of Art, the Wallace Collection in London, the Royal Armouries in Leeds, and the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City.
[src:armour/armour] Horse armour could be made in whole or in part of cuir bouilli (hardened leather), but surviving examples of this are especially rare.
[src:armour/armour] War elephants were first used in ancient times without armour, but armour was introduced because elephants injured by enemy weapons would often flee the battlefield.
[src:armour/armour] Elephant armour was often made from hardened leather, which was fitted onto an individual elephant while moist, then dried to create a hardened shell.
[src:armour/armour] Alternatively, metal armour pieces were sometimes sewn into heavy cloth.
[src:armour/armour] Later lamellar armour (small overlapping metal plates) was introduced.
[src:armour/armour] Full plate armour was not typically used due to its expense and the danger of the animal overheating.
